<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="7">Diagnosis</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="7">Distinguished from all other rivulids by the following unambiguous synapomorphies (Costa, 2006a): presence of filamentous rays on the posterior margin of anal fin in females (vs. absent in females), caudal fin lanceolate and asymmetrical due to expansion of ventral portion of fin in males (vs. caudal fin rounded or subtruncate; dorsal and ventral portion symmetrical), and a unique color pattern consisting of a bar on posterior portion of caudal peduncle, posteriorly extending over dorsal and ventral margins of caudal fin in males (vs. never a similar color pattern).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="7">Included species</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="7">
Only the type species, 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="myersi">Simpsonichthys myersi</taxonomicName>
(Carvalho).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="7">Distribution</paragraph>
